name: Raghav
text:
Remember that life is not a rat race. Diseases don‚Äôt care whether you‚Äôre rich, poor, pretty or not. Your money won‚Äôt always save you. 

Remember... (n/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember that you don‚Äôt travel just for yourself. Every time you step outside your house, people around you are affected.

Remember to take care of your environment. It has a way to taking back what you‚Äôve stolen from it. 
(10/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember to vote. Vote for a government that focuses on infrastructure and values its citizens. A government that isn‚Äôt afraid to take strong actions. No government can please everyone, but remember to use your vote wisely. 
(9/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember, guns won‚Äôt always protect you. In the end, the only thing that will is you‚Äôre own common sense. 

Remember to take things seriously.
(8/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember your friends. Those who checked in on you, reminded you & encouraged you to do the right thing. The ones who cancelled important events be it a marriage, a birthday, or any celebration. 

Remember the ones who couldn‚Äôt even say one last goodbye to their loved ones. (7/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember all the corporates and the rich that did nothing at a time when people needed them the most. The people who thought making one video to boost their social media was enough. Those who had nothing to say when they didn‚Äôt have anything to promote/sell. 
(6/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember the people who thought of this as a money making opportunity. Greed can only make you rich for a short time. Tables will eventually turn. Don‚Äôt forget how they treated you, when they will need your business again. 
(5/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember that family matters and sooner or later you will end up with them. 

Remember the people who were there for you. The doctors, the caregivers, the runners, the officials, the guards, and those in the service industry. 
(4/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember to look beyond Instagram and other Social Media. Your life is around you and not in your phones and tablets. 

Remember that life‚Äôs too unpredictable to hold grudges. Use this time to call a long lost friend or two. 
(3/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember not to glamourise leaving corporate and 9to5 jobs for travel. It doesn‚Äôt work for everyone. Now, more than ever, we need people who are professionals, in the ‚Äúreal‚Äù world, in 9to5 jobs (who are working 24x7). 
(2/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Remember! 

Remember that you need to save (money), for moments like these. All those memes and posts about ‚Äúyou can earn money later, travel now‚Äù mean nothing. (1/n)

text: @arvjpr True. In this case all were from our country. And yes, all paid projects. Fees was discussed and agreed upon in advance.

name: Raghav
text:
So, point being, there are always two sides to every coin. 

But I will also say that this is not the case with everyone. There have been a few, okay one, enthusiastic freelancer I‚Äôve come across so far. 

Still early stages, but let‚Äôs see how that pans out. (N/n)

name: Raghav
text: Communication on the whole is extremely poor. Email responses can take anywhere from a few days to weeks. I‚Äôm still waiting for a freelancer who is supposed to get back with topic ideas. It‚Äôs now been three weeks. This is after all the terms and conditions were agreed upon. (6/n)

name: Raghav
text:
I got one email that went on & on about a website they wrote for. How many hits it got. How big it was. However, they‚Äôve only ever written 1 article for that website. 

Someone wrote that they don‚Äôt have anything to show but ‚Äúwriting is something they always wanted to do.‚Äù (5/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Most of them failed to answer simple questions asked initially, and had to be reminded a few times before they gave essential information - such as rate/fee expected, for example. 

I also noticed many freelancers don‚Äôt have a portfolio of any kind. 

(4/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Why would anyone say something like that to a client, I don‚Äôt know. 

They also asked for a ‚Äúfew days‚Äù to finish the article. That was 12 days back. 

Quite a few sent emails as if they are sending a text to their best friend. 

(3/n)

name: Raghav
text:
Sad to say I can‚Äôt put the whole blame on clients anymore. 

A few trends I noticed while dealing with freelancers:

Lack of professionalism. A freelancer messaged me saying they are late with a submission because they are ‚Äúbusy with another important project.‚Äù (2/n)

name: Raghav
text:
So, I‚Äôve been extremely open about my views regarding freelance clients, and their lack of professionalism, in the past. 

This past month I had the opportunity to be in their shoes. In the process of hiring writers for my blog, I came across quite a few fellow freelancers.(1/n)

name: Raghav
text: @BookLuster @PhalinShah First, restaruants invited bloggers to review, gave free food and what not. Once it bcame a norm, bloggers started demanding, and now restaurants complain about this. In the end it comes back to the person with money. Brands should stop looking at numbers and focus on content,.

name: Raghav
text: @BookLuster @PhalinShah I believe it is the brands/companies/PR who are at fault. It's all about the numbers game. Bloggers or Publications want hits, so they can claim to be influencers, which means more money from advertisers and brands. The same happened with food blogging...

name: Raghav
text: @BookLuster @PhalinShah That's our society now. Get a few thousand followers and people think they are celebrity/influencer and everyone "following" them is a fan. A blogger becomes a writer and then a journalist. Sadly, I've seen it happen more in our country than elsewhere.

name: Raghav
text: @PhalinShah I agree with this as well. But the fact remains that if a journalist writes "bad", that doesn't take away his/her credentials from them. Similarly, if a blogger writes well (journalistic level), it doesn't mean they can call themselves a journalist.

name: Raghav
text: @PhalinShah I agree. Unfortunately once content writers or bloggers get published in magazines the line gets even more fuzzy. I always feels it‚Äôs the client who should be aware of this. Also, to call oneself a journalist, some sort of formal education/degree is required, according to me.

name: Raghav
text:
Measure a place by how it moves you. 

Don‚Äôt worry whether it is touristy or offbeat. 

Some roads less travelled take you nowhere and some places filled with people leave a lasting impression on your lives. 

Stop labelling travel!

name: Raghav
text:
This lady was at least honest and admitted she was learning new stuff and getting to understand the other side of the story. 

However, I wonder what does the average person really think blogging is?
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
And then the whole spiel about how they are a startup or have tight budgets. 

Seriously, when people say this to bloggers do they actually think we make loads of cash?

Or are they confused about the Free in Freelancer?
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
For a blogger, all that is usually a one man/woman job. In addition to that we have overhead expenses that relate to various expenditures of owing a blog, equipment, time etc. 

Our content is free for everyone to read. Yes, bloggers do get advertisement options but it‚Äôs peanuts.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
Then I went on to explain that the writer who visited their tour went back and write and submitted the content. 

Someone then edited it maybe, a different person was the photog, actually publishing it was another person/team, and then social media and what not by more people.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
First I told her that the people who visited them were employees or writers of publication and in all probability their company paid them for the trip + salary. 

Both these publications/websites are profitable organisations. Plus one would have to buy to read a Nat Geo.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
Their reply to the prices quoted was something on the lines on ‚Äúoh we had Nat Geo and LBB cover is and they paid us for the tours. I guess they were just kind.‚Äù

I kept my calm and explained to the lady what blogging involves. Thankfully she was receptive of my explanation.

name: Raghav
text:
It still surprises me how clueless a lot of people are about blogging and all that it involves. 

Today I was approached by someone who wanted to work together to promote their travel business. 

I gave them some possibilities including the option of paid guest/sponsored posts.

text:
A car is moving very slowly in the middle of the road. 

I honk out of necessity.

Nothing happens. I begin to overtake from the side.

Maybe he‚Äôs busy with the controls?

Maybe he‚Äôs on the phone?

He IS busy.

name: Raghav
text:
N/n Now you can make of this what you want, but I felt it was a missed opportunity on so many levels for the Brand. 

I really can‚Äôt understand what goes on when events like such are organised, but to me it seems quite plain and simple, yet things are often trivial. 

Oh well...
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
12/n I did the company some Social Media love out of guilt and because the product is good, but I really couldn‚Äôt get around to inviting me (and others). 

They could have sent me a free code sitting in their office actually.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
11/n This is a feedback form for the PR company, NOT for the Brand whose event it was on the day. 

I told them that I never received one, which was the truth. 

They said if it‚Äôs okay for them to send an email version. 

I said yes. 

That was the last I heard from them.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
10/n Me being me, I only used one of the codes I was given. 

A few days later I received a call from the PR person. I thought here we go, now the request for a blog will come. 

That was not to be the case. 

They asked if I had filled the feedback form for the PR company.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
9/n I looked around for another minute or two and with no one to really guide about anything I walked out. 

I wasn‚Äôt the only one who looked clueless. 

I had been there for about 20 minutes and left with about Rs. 4000,- worth of freebies.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
8/n I walked out. Some people went straight to the drinks (non alcoholic) and snacks. Some genuinely seemed interested in the product.

Me? I felt lost. It was a little too crowded for my liking and I didn‚Äôt really know what I was expected to do as a blogger who had been invited.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
7/n Just as we‚Äôre getting up to see the ‚Äúproducts‚Äù on display around us, we were told to stop.

They had a surprise for us. 

A little code for a certain amount to order stuff off their website etc. I was handed two and if I wanted could have managed three or four.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
6/n The person next to me commented something to the line of ‚ÄúWho is this blogger, no one even knows her. Why would they call her?‚Äù

The presentation ended after about 15 minutes of me being there. There were about 30 odd people present.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
5/n I reached the 2 hour event an hour late. The presentation was nearing its end. I filled a form and sat down towards the end of the room.

A few bloggers who had been contacted earlier were called on staged and presented goodies. 

The other bloggers had looks to kill!
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
4/n The day before the event I was able to confirm and shot them a message. Also informed them I‚Äôll be a little late. 

On the day, I received a call confirming my presence. I checked again if it‚Äôs okay to attend the event about an hour late. 

They said yes.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
3/n As is the case often, I gave a lukewarm response and informed them that being a Dad, weekend preference is to the kids so I cannot guarantee. 

I received a few emails in the followings weeks requesting once again that I attend.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
2/n I received an email from a PR that first applauded my wonderful blog and how inspirational it was. It was obvious they had never been on it and had jotted my name from a blogger list somewhere. 

I was bored at the time, and curiosity got the better of me.
location: Place(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, id='64231a922dea526e', url='https://api.twitter.com/1.1/geo/id/64231a922dea526e.json', place_type='city', name='Gurgaon', full_name='Gurgaon, India', country_code='IN', country='India', contained_within=[], bounding_box=BoundingBox(_api=<tweepy.api.API object at 0x00000141CF45C3C8>, type='Polygon', coordinates=[[[76.707671, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.199529], [77.241711, 28.537521], [76.707671, 28.537521]]]), attributes={})

name: Raghav
text:
1/n Figured enough time has gone by that I can talk about a PR/Brand event that I ‚Äúattended‚Äù a while back. 

This is not a rant. No one did anything wrong, to me at least. 

It‚Äôs more of a partially funny anecdote and a look at the whole influencer/brand relationship.

name: Raghav
text:
Telling signs that the "guest post" request email you got is a sneaky link request:
1. Will refer to you as "Admin" or just Hi
2. Praise your blog more than your mom does
3. Praise how good a writer they are and have the perfect post for you
4. Won't mention any link at first

name: Raghav
text:
Often I take time replying back to brands and PR. No, not because I'm busy or snobbish, it's just that I want to send a sarcastically humorous "NO" to them and my brain just isn't feeling funny enough for that.

Point being, if you haven't heard from me, wait a little longer.

name: Raghav
text: @anindya0909 @DivsiGupta But, many a times content doesn't matter, it's about getting the link in or just posting anything. I mean people do read CB in millions so let's face it, the audience isn't too choosy either.

name: Raghav
text: @anindya0909 @DivsiGupta True and the fact that people don't know their own worth. Took me a while to realize I could charge a lot more than what I was previously.

name: Raghav
text:
In continuation;
First came the whole "we will give you exposure" for the longest time. Then the "Barter" system started. Then, there was the Rs 500 for basically whatever you do, and now it's gone up to Rs 2500 max for writing and hosting a link. https://t.co/EwqzpGbGcz

name: Raghav
text: @anindya0909 @DivsiGupta That and a lot of people still don't understand Social Media. For them it's easy to just say "look he/she must be popular if they have xyz followers". No wonder content creation agencies are on a rise now.

name: Raghav
text: @anindya0909 @DivsiGupta I wonder why is it that THEY don't know about this? I mean the stories I can tell about this. Brands are clueless and thus get taken for a ride based on "numbers".

name: Raghav
text: @theuntourists Unfortunately the amount of competition and hesitance between bloggers to share information is why this is happening. Very few willing to share details of how much they charge.

name: Raghav
text:
PR/Brand: Must have 10K+ Followers, X daily page hits, SM account stats, previous work, rate per word, where else you can post, published work...

Me: Ok, and how much do you usually pay for content?

PR/Brand: Rs 500 for 2000 words / We only do barter / exposure 

Me: ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
